segments.text: And that is with Fred McClure.
I re-recorded.
So y'all cooled your heels?
Yeah.
And, you know, he was the Uncle Charlie of that place.
Wow.
I never saw anything like it.
Well, we eventually worked out some things.
And as a matter of fact, there was a very interesting result.
One of the professors who went down there, I think it was Binger, I think it was he,
taught down there and he came back with a report that was stunning about how
the rooms weren't air conditioned, although there were air conditioners there, but they didn't work.
And what turned out to be the fact was that they had used maintenance money for other purposes.
In any event, it led to a big, and you know as much about that as I do, what happened, a big turnover.

or did you did you ever have to cope with the realities of the services and the stations reporting to the system where the dean of agriculture reported to the campus something slid it into my mind and it I was asking you about the stations and oh yeah that was a serious problem I mentioned a director who dictated

tried to dictate salaries even in the veterinary medicine school if he had a small piece we had a problem over Kunkel took credit for this but I don't know if it was he who actually instigated it but the problem of designating professorial titles to people out in the experiment stations
And we never did resolve that, but it was something that happened some time ago, probably in the early days of Kunkel's deanship.
I think we eliminated it, but there was probably a question of whether they would have representation in the Senate.
Now, it'd be okay if they were joint appointments, but there are some who weren't even joint appointments.
As a matter of fact, I had gone through at the University of Tennessee a situation where in the last year or so that I was there, I was a senator.
And the Extension Service dominated the Senate because they had all of these people all over the state of Tennessee.
So there was that kind of thing.

If you had dictatorial authority, you're the emperor and don't have to explain it to the voters, how would you organize administratively the ag and engineering experiment stations and extension services?
Where would they report?
To the dean.
And then the dean would report to the?
Vice president for academic affairs.
Chancellor.
All right.
Then, now I'm being the devil's advocate.
How would then anyone anywhere else within the Texas A&M system, how would they possibly get any research money from one of the experiment stations?
Well, I really have not thought that all through, but that would be a problem.
You know, I suppose it could be worked out, but I saw some, we had some pretty nasty problems as a result of not having jurisdiction over the extension services or the...
I think I'm discovering that one of the consistent problems for 40, 50 years
has been that organizational structure.
Yeah.
And that only under Rudder and Williams, when they were head CEO of both the system and the campus, did we not have it.
That's right.
And now it seems to me at least that the system is very, very, very personnel heavy.
Oh boy, that's, you're absolutely right.
An enormous amount of money has gone into the system.
And it did happen in the 80s.
That's when it really took off.
All right, back to other proud moments, victories that you recall back in your day.
Did we leave any out?
Probably, but I'll think about them later.
All right, now I'm going to ask the negative.
Which deans would you put on your merit page to give special praise to?
Certainly, Gordon when he was in Geosciences.
That's Gordon Eaton.
Yeah, Gordon Eaton and Mel Friedman.
Mel Friedman in Geosciences.
Yeah, I thought they both did a fine job.
Mews when he was dean.
Ann Mobley, I thought, did a good job.
And now, what's the president dean's name?
He's good.
He really is good.
He was the vice president at Houston.
Oh, yes.
The accountant.
Yes.
I can't think of his name, but I remember trying to help recruit him back in the late 70s as a faculty member.
Yeah, he's a class act.
Yes, yes.
That College of Business almost runs by itself.
One of the things I observed about it is they don't really participate in the rest of the university.
They're out doing their own thing.
If you round up the usual suspects for a committee, with the exception of a waynetter, one or two like that,
you run out of names real quickly.
In agriculture, you get lots of them.
In liberal arts, you get a bunch of them.
Liberal arts, Dean?
I don't remember one that's outstanding.
Architecture, I think there have, architecture is just a disaster area for a long time.
Engineering?
Well, again, you know, poor old Bob followed Benson.
He didn't have a chance because it was Skip Porter there.
Samson?
I mean, Science?
Veterinary Medicine?
Oh, I think John Shattuck was very good.
Shelton was a good old boy, but he'd come over and apologize for asking for salary increases.
He wasn't a fighter for his college, but he was a very nice man.
I liked him a lot.
But Shattuck was a good one, and he was fourth on the list, which made for some problems with acceptance by the faculty.
I can't, I didn't know Woody as a dean.
Fallon played games.
Okay.
And he's paid a price for it, for that kind of thing.
Let's see, who am I, I thought Corrigan did a good job with education.
He, the day that I got back from my on campus interview at El Paso,
We landed, and an hour later, I was to meet him at the same airport here to begin his visit as the prospective dean.
Really?
And in the ones that I led, I always insisted we try to follow, as much as possible, exactly the same schedule for everybody.
So it would be equal experiences.
And we would go into the little mini theater in the Rudder Tower.
Rutter Center, and it would be an introductory session with the prospective dean, and I would introduce him or her.
They would make a presentation about themselves, their background, and what they thought were the major issues before, in this case, education, and then make conversation.
I'd try to say, you're not supposed to quiz them this time.
And when I sat down, I was so tired, I said to myself,
Mr. Dean Corrigan, you'd better be pretty good or I may go to sleep.
Well, an hour later, I was wide awake because he was so interesting.
I thought he, I was much impressed with him.
Dean, we belong to the same church, Dean is really knowledgeable about what's going on in higher education.
He and McDonald didn't, McDonald had nothing but disdain for the College of Education, and Dean stepped down, I think, because of Donald, who was, I wouldn't rank him high as a provost.
I always wondered why he was selected.
I'll tell you a story about that.
Vanderburg promised that if I had Mobley on the list, he'd pick him.
But Mobley, Jimmy was sitting next to him.
I shouldn't be telling this.
Let's see, were there any other deans that we left out that you wanted that deserve high praise?
I think John Fackler fought for his college.
Which college was that?
Science.
Science.
And did a, it was some one way he said that if we gave him a budget of infinity he'd exceed it.
But I thought he was a pretty effective dean.
All right, looking back on those 10 years, do you remember any moments of joy that may have been a brief moment where you said, oh, boy, I'm glad I was there?
In that little piece that's in this thing, the night we were counting the votes on the Senate was an electrifying experience.
It was over in a room in, Claude Davis had headed up the program to see how it would go.
And it was over in architecture, and it was an exciting evening.
There were lots of things like when we had Bart Giamatti here and I put up the money to host a dinner at Fish Richards for the English department.
and that was a fun experience because they were really, the faculty really enjoyed it I think.
I thought that John McDermott did a fabulous job, stayed often?
Well, did a fabulous job of being the first speaker of the Senate and then the perfect combination of
what's his name in agriculture that we were talking about earlier became the second speaker Murray Milford Murray Milford
with his crew cut and all.
He smoothed things out then with the regents as a speaker went to the Board of Regents meeting.
Because McDermott was, by Aggie standards, quote, an outsider.
But Murray, an insider.
He grew up in Texas, went to A&M and so forth.
Cadet, colonel, or whatever.
Do you remember any moments when there was a now amusing snafu
when something just didn't go the way it was planned.
Gee.
I can't remember one in which.
Where somebody forgot their speech or didn't show up or.
got to the wrong place.
I guess I sort of blocked them from memory if they were dead.
Do you remember any regents' meetings that were highly significant?
I remember one of the earliest ones.
It was shortly after Vandiver had been hired.
Bill McKenzie came up to Chuck and me and said, don't worry men, we'll get rid of him within the year.
I don't know, we may edit that out too, but I remember that.
For the most part, I wasn't there when Jarvis Miller was terminated, so for the most part it was kind of dull.
And then after a while we didn't go, we weren't allowed to go, just as well.
Okay, about to wind it up then.
Who would you like to thank?
If you, whether they're living or not, who do you wish you could thank for what has happened in these years here that you've known?
Providence, I guess.
I don't know, I've been lucky in some, in a lot of respects.
You know, outside of parents, I mean, they certainly had a lot.
Oh, I was meaning Aggie types.
Aggie types.
I really appreciated Mac Prescott in my early, early years as a dean of faculty.

John Pearson played a role as I said we did get out of sorts after a while but then we made up people like John McDermott was a great supporter of mine for reasons I never quite understood but I don't know there's so many people that who were so supportive and so friendly it's hard to
Pick them up.
People like Gary Hart, of whom I'm very fond.
Murray Milford.
Bruce Schaefer.
I mean, there are a lot of people that helped.
All you had to do was ask them.
I really did enjoy the relationships with faculty and found them always to be so supportive and so eager to.
Okay, two more questions.
Next, the last one is let's make believe that I gave you a million dollar check and said there's only one restriction on the check.
You must give it to Texas A&M, but you decide
what the money would go to help.
I used to fight for money that was with no strings attached.
And so that's kind of a hard one.
I guess I would put it in faculty development leaves.
You're the first person that's thought of that one.
Well, I was involved with that.
No, I understand.
I understand that.
I really... You know, major schools do have significant programs, and we haven't got one yet.
I don't know if we ever will.
But if we want to be the super school that this recent pronouncement had to do with, the Vision 2020 or whatever it is, 2000...

that's one of the areas we need to work on let me let me add a question then you now are emperor again and you can give advice to the leadership of the decision makers about A&M what advice would you give them today one thing I would like to see them have and it's not an original idea with me it's one that Tulane had I would strongly urge
that there be created a board of visitors drawn from the highest echelons to come in and advise the board and the president.
I proposed that in this 1992 or 3 thing that Calhoun was involved in.
We were talking about the other day at coffee.
It never got anywhere, of course.
But I think getting some really top-rated people from industry, from people who really understand, you know, big-time people, that would be the one thing I would want to see.
Right.
Last question.
Looking back, what effect did it have on your life that you accepted this appointment at Texas A&M?
Well, obviously, it was a very positive effect.
In retrospect, I know I made the right decision.
I've really enjoyed the years I've been here.
I've been well taken care of.
I think the family enjoyed it.
Let me close then by, on behalf of all of the people who have maroon blood, to thank you for your part in making this place better.
Thank you.
